<DOC><DOCNO> AP891021-0164 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-10-21-89 2226EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Hayes     10-21 0135</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Obit-Hayes,0138</SECOND><HEAD>Former Federal Reserve President Dead at 79</HEAD><DATELINE>NEW CANAAN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Alfred Hayes, the former president ofthe Federal Reserve Bank of New York, died Saturday at his home. Hewas 79.   Hayes suffered from Alzheimer's disease and Parkinson's diseaseand had been in a nursing home for about four years, said RichardHoenig, a spokesman for the bank.   Hayes was educated at Harvard and Yale universities. He returnedto New York City in 1933 after a year in England as a Rhodesscholar and started working in the bond department at the NationalCity Bank of New York, which later became Citibank.   In 1956, he was appointed to the Federal Reserve and servedthere until 1975. During the same period, he was vice chairman ofthe Federal Open Market Committee.</TEXT></DOC>